Part 6: Make my plot a better plot

The goal is to take my sad looking plot and make it better! If you’d like an example, here is a tweet I came across of someone who gave a talk about how to zhoosh up your ggplots.

chocolate %>%
    ggplot(aes(
        x = as.factor(review_date),
        y = rating,
        fill = review_date)) + 
theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90,size =12, colour = "black", vjust = 0.5, hjust = 1, face = "bold"), 
axis.title.y = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold"), legend.title = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold"), 
        legend.text = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold", colour = "dark blue"), 
        axis.text.y = element_text(colour = "black", size = 12, face = "bold")) +
    geom_violin()+ geom_boxplot(width= .1, fill= "gray") +labs(title = "Chocolate Review Date",subtitle = "2020 and 2021 have the overall highest reviews since 2006", x= "Review Date", y="Rating")

- Added a title to the graph using the function labs(title) - Added a subtitle to give the main results of the graph using the function labs(subtitle) - Change the x-axis title form “as.factor(review_date)” to “Review Date” - Change the axis and legend font to size to 12 and made it bold to be more clear for readers using the function theme(). - Change the color of the numbers inside of the legend to make the graph more appealing to readers using the function legend.text - Change the date in x-axis from horizontal position to vertical position to have more space between each other using element_text(angle = 90)inside of the theme function. - Added geom_boxplot() in color gray to help visualize the median of the plot.
